post_text:
JLHS had a fantastic start to the 2020/21 school year!! Thanks to everyone for the support and understanding as we work our way through some tumultuous times.
Clarification on the student learning logs: teachers are providing recommended timeframes for assignments and projects. These recommendations are designed to help students manage their time as our goal is to achieve 360 minutes of engagement each day that a student is working in a remote setting. Please understand that these recommendations are just a reference and that we understand that students may need more or less time than what is recommended. Please record the estimated time that the student was engaged with the activity on the log even if it is different from the recommendation. Please have students turn in their log to their HawkTime teacher on the first day they return to face to face setting each week.
Thank You!!

post_text:
JES enrollment Information:

Online enrollment is available July 29th through August 7th on PowerSchool through our USD346 website. We recommend online enrollment. If you are unable to enroll online, the Jayhawk Elementary office will be open Monday, August 3rd - Thursday, August 6, for enrollment from 10am to 6pm. Please use the following schedule for enrolling your elementary student(s):

Monday, August 3rd: Last name beginning with A – D
Tuesday, August 4th: Last name beginning with E – K
Wednesday, August 5th: Last name beginning with L – R
Thursday, August 6th: Last name beginning with S – Z

We will be practicing social distancing in the building. The lunchroom will be available for space to fill out enrollment forms. We are asking that only one parent per family come into the building to enroll. If there are too many in the building we may ask that you wait in your car while you are in line to enroll.

post_text:
July 15th 2020
Parents and Students: As the number of active cases of COVID-19 continues to rise and hospitals in parts of the state fill to capacity with patients affected by this virus, Governor Kelly and the Kansas Department of Health and Environment have decided to push back the reopening of schools. On Monday, a record spike pushed Kansas over 20,000 cases with nearly 300 deaths. Schools will reopen after Labor Day on September 8th. We will release more information later on Enrollment dates, Drivers Ed, and what the school year will look like. We are still mandated to provide 1116 hours of instruction to the students and to be clear this is a delay in the reopening of schools.

We are still mandated to provide 1116 hours of instruction to the students and to be clear this is a delay in the reopening of schools.

Update - The USD 346 administration is very concerned with the increase in Covid-19 infections in Kansas. While we have not changed our plans for the July 18 Graduation as of yet, please check our communication platforms frequently in case we do have need to make such a change.
Due to the nature of our planned Prom, we are questioning the ability to ensure student safety during such an event and will be making a decision in the next few days as to whether we will proceed with Prom. We apologize for the uncertainty, but will do our best to keep our students safe during the pandemic. We will update frequently through our communication portals.

post_text:
It’s time to start Summer Workouts! YIPPEE! We are looking forward to seeing you at our first week of conditioning, June 9th and June 11th from 6:00-7:00 p.m. We will be making some modifications from our usual early morning/weight room format to keep everyone safe and healthy, but we are excited about the opportunity to get together and work on getting faster and stronger. This workout is for ANY GIRL that wants to come, 7th-12th grades, and ANY sport!
Here are some things to keep in mind:
1. If you are sick, have a temperature, or believe you have been exposed, please stay home.
2. We will be limiting groups to 15 or less, but don’t worry, we will have a coach to lead your group.
3. Bring your own water bottle. NO SHARING of water bottles will be allowed.

Come see us on Tuesday at 6:00 AT THE TRACK for a great workout and some even better friendships!

If you have questions, please call Christa Holt at (620)-224-0208.

post_text: Parents and students 4-17-2020. We are making some small changes to our food service deliveries. Hopefully, these changes will make receiving your meals more convenient and keep everyone safer. Effective Monday April 20th we will deliver meals twice a week (Mondays and Tuesdays) instead of 4 days a week. Monday routes will remain the same, but, will deliver a full week of meals (5 breakfast and 5 lunch) to the bus stops which will eliminate the need to have a meal delivery on Thursday. Tuesday bus routes will also remain the same and those kids will also receive a full week of meals and not have a delivery on Friday. Car-line will still run on Wednesdays at JES from 11 am to noon. In conclusion, beginning the week of April 20th there will be NO Thursday or Friday bus deliveries for the remainder of the school year.

Jayhawk USD 346
April 8 at 2:31 PM ·

Parents and Students 4-8-2020. We need your help to keep our kids safe and slow down the spread of COVID-19. Most of you are doing an awesome job of staying at home so we can get back to normalcy quicker. Some of you still believe this will not impact your life or a loved one even if you are a carrier of the virus. USD 346 has been working closely with the Linn County Sheriffs office to report any student gatherings that are not a part of the stay home order. Attached you will find an overview of the Kansas Stay Home order, please take heed to these guidelines written by our Health officials. We are blessed to live in a community where Law Enforcement, Health Officials and Schools work closely with one another to keep families safe.

post_text: Parents and students 4-3-2020. This week we fed over 4000 meals to the children of our district. Teachers have rolled out learning for your students and we are desperately trying to find a "new normal" for school. As for food service about 3 to 5 families a day "miss the bus". If you know you are not going to be present to get your meals please call the school and cancel your order for that day. We expect your child to be at the bus stop on time and should not have to call or honk the horn before they come out of the house. Educationally, we expect all students to participate in the continuous learning opportunities offered by the district to the fullest extent possible, without placing additional burdens and hardships on our families. If you have trouble with connectivity or understanding assignments please email or call our staff and we will gladly assist students and families overcome barriers and obstacles. On the lighter side, one student recently asked me, "do you really expect us to do our assignments?" My answer, "only if you want to pass your class and graduate".

On the lighter side, one student recently asked me, "do you really expect us to do our assignments?" My answer, "only if you want to pass your class and graduate".

JLHS Continuous Learning Plan has started rolling out to students. Please be patient with us as we are in uncharted territory. Please understand that each teacher faces unique challenges based upon his or content and the needs of the class being rolled out. Our intent is to release material and classwork slowly so as to not overwhelm students who are also facing a reality unlike anything they are familiar with.
We know that what works for one student or family may not work for others and that we will need time and communication to get those plans in place for everyone.
Teachers and staff have your best interest at heart. They want to help you and they want you to succeed. Feel free to communicate issues or concerns with your teacher or with Mr. Thomas and Mr. Holt.
We WILL get through these tough times by working together.

Reminder: there is No School for students next week March 23rd through the 27th. On Monday, March 23rd we will release a survey to gather information of your Internet capabilities in your home. We will also ask if you would like free breakfast and lunch delivered for your child. We are working on a plan to complete your students final weeks of school. We will use 3 delivery strategies to provide continuous learning: 1) take-home learning packets 2) online learning and 3) Limited face-to-face instruction. Please continue to monitor our website, district app, and/or district facebook page for the latest updates.

Finally, questions have surfaced concerning your child’s personal belongings and medications in the school. For medications, our school nurse will contact you to set up a time to meet at school and pick up medications. Access to your child’s belongings may occur the week of March 30th, if access to buildings is still allowed by our health agencies. We realize this is an unprecedented time, working together we will accomplish success.

post_text:
USD #346 Student athletes and parents - we received the following email from KSHSAA this afternoon.

To: Member Schools
RE: Suspension of Spring Activities/Athletics

COVID 19 – Updated information for spring activities

Effective Monday, March 16, all spring sports and activities are suspended through Sunday, March 22. This includes cancellation of all practices and competitions for this week. This prohibition is consistent with KSDE and governmental guidance and may be extended, should conditions warrant. Please note spring sports team members are prohibited from club or outside team participation and practice during this period. Not only would such outside participation be contrary to handbook rule, it would be contrary to the very reason activities are cancelled during the time we seek to mitigate potential transfer of the contagion.
